  "prompt": "When does a Senate motion require 3/5 vote?",
  "response": "In the U.S. Senate, a motion generally requires a 3/5 vote (typically 60 out of 100 senators) when it comes to overcoming a filibuster or cloture motion. A filibuster is a tactic used by senators to extend debate on a piece of legislation, effectively delaying or blocking a vote. To end this debate and proceed to a vote, a senator must file for cloture, which requires the support of 60 senators to be invoked.\n\nAdditionally, certain other instances may require a supermajority, such as constitutional amendments or to override a presidential veto, but the most common situation where a 3/5 vote is needed is to limit debate and move forward to a final vote on legislation.",
